Personal Disclosure¶

I'd like to start this off with a disclosure: Although I am not and have never been a user of marijuana, I do believe that it should be legalized for a variety of reasons, some of which I will explain throughout this tutorial.

The purpose of this tutorial is to give you the tools you need to analyze data and explore trends. While I would like to use this data to advocate for marijuana legalization, note that this and most any data can be selectively manipulated for any purpose. My hope is that you, the reader, uses this power I will show you for good (creating information) and not for evil (creating misinformation). By giving you the sources of my data and methods of analysis, I am inviting you to go through the data yourself and see if you come to the same conclusions as I.

Ethics¶

To get a visual sense for how data can be manipulated to show any sort of correlation, you might want to check out this. It is a site which shows spurious correlations between variables which logically shouldn't have any bearing on each other, for example: the per capita cheese consumption is highly correlated with the number of people who died by becoming tangled in their bedsheets over time. These two datasets are highly unrelated, but the moral of the story is that if you seek for correlations, you will find them. Also see this explained xkcd on the ease in finding a correlation to back up your beliefs. If you need further background on pvalues to understand the xkcd comic, check out this explanation here. For the comic, and for my project, the null hypothesis is that there is no correlation and the alternate hypothesis is that there is a correlation

In short: make sure to create a solid hypothesis to test out a potential correlation rather than wading through data to find a correlation that fits your story. In order to build a sensible hypothesis, it's critical to obtain domain knowledge or other words to learn the fundamentals of whatever you would like to research. Back to me, while I have not consumed marijuana, I do have some domain knowledge due to lengthy conversations with users and background research over the past several years.

Now that I've reviewed a bit about data ethics, let's get to it.

1. Motivation for research¶

I had previously analyzed Baltimore crime data and I noticed something startling about it - at least around 10% of arrests in Baltimore in the year I analyzed, 2015, had been for the sole purpose of enforcing marijuana laws. I believe that this is morally wrong due to the medical benefits of the plant.

First, I will lead you through how I got the results that I did on the Baltimore crime data. Then, I will observe a jurisdiction in which marijuana was made illegal to see the effect on other crime.

I propose that legalization of marijuana would be correlated with several positive effects:

  • If marijuana is allowed out of the black market and into the streets, I hypothesize that this will weaken organized crime by cutting off a source of income. This is unfortunately not easy to prove in the short term, but I do predict that we will see this trend as time goes on
  • Without the need to arrests marijuana users, I hypothesize that police will have more time to focus on harmful issues and that other crime will go down
  • Marijuana has a generally calming effect on people, which I also believe can help reduce violent crime
  • Marijuana can help people get off of addicted substances and back into a healthy balance

Note that in this dataset, the sex and race columns were reversed. It's important to note that data is ultimately measured, collected, and synthesized by humans, even if it is done with technology built by humans, and there is always the chance for human or technology error. We would like to swap these two columns to get the correct result. In this dataset, there are two categories for sex: 'M' and 'F' for Male and Female and six for race, 'B', 'W', 'A', 'U', 'I', and 'H' for Black, White, Asian, Unknown, American Indian, and Hispanic.

1.1 The issue of missing data¶

Missing data can fall into one of the following categories:

  • Missing completely at random (MCAR)
    • Data is missing for entirely random reasons unrelated to the type of data stored. For example, if during a data transfer of unsorted data, an unreliable protocol was used and random datapoints were dropped, this could potentially be MCAR. If the data was actually MCAR, we could simply drop the datapoints and move on, but very few missing data are actually ever MCAR.
  • Missing at random (MAR)
    • Data may be missing but we have a hunch for why it may be missing based on other observed data. For example, if we ask students their expected grade in a particular class this semester and their GPA, they may be willing to reveal their GPA but perhaps not all will reveal their grade in specific. If we have enough data on the relationship between GPA and grade and potentially other factors for the other students in the course, we may be able to estimate the grade based on the GPA even for those students who weren't forthcoming with the information
  • Missing not at random (MNAR)
    • Data is neither MCAR nor MAR, but there is some relationship between why data is missing based on that type of data alone - for example, people involved in a long-term study on a medication for elderly people may die in the midst of the study and therefore will have missing data which can't necessarily be found solely from the other data collected

For more information on this, check out this link.

Unfortunately, categorizing the missing data takes significant domain expertise, and while I could postulate all day on why certain Baltimore crime data was missing from 2015, I simply do not have the proper background to analyze this.

1.2 Dealing with the missing data¶

While I will not try to extrapolate for why the data was missing, or try to figure out what sort of crime data may even be entirely unreported, or not even recorded in this dataset, I will deal with this in a straightforward way.

If the data were to be missing completely at random, there would be a good chance that the percentage of marijuana arrests in the remaining data would hold for the entire dataset. This would be a sort of middle bound.

If the data missing is entirely made up of arrests having nothing to do with marijuana, that would be the lower bound. As in, if I divide the number of verifiably marijuana-related arrests by the number of arrests in total, this would be the minimum proportion of marijuana-related arrests possible in the dataset, since the assumption would be that none of the unknown datapoints were related to marijuana.

The upper bound would technically be if every single unknown arrest was for marijuana, but this would be highly unusual and highly unlikely. It is possible that there is a higher or lower proportion of marijuana arrests in the unknown data, but there's no way to know for certain without the ability to talk to the people involved in recording and preparing the data.

For the purposes of getting some sort of range for the true value, I will look at both the 'middle bound' and the 'lower bound'.

# create a copy of the original data
arrest_table_drugs = arrest_table.copy()
# create a function which will return 'true' if the
# data falls under one of the categories mentioned above
def drug_related(category):
    return category == '87-Narcotics' \
        or category == '87O-Narcotics (Outside)' \
        or category == '23-Unauthorized Use'
# create a mask which only include these three categories
drug_mask = arrest_table_drugs.apply(
    lambda row: drug_related(row['incidentOffense']),
    axis = 1)
# use mask to filter the arrest_table_drugs data
arrest_table_drugs = arrest_table_drugs[drug_mask]
# print out first three rows of the data
arrest_table_drugs.head(5)

1.4 Finding marijuana arrests - charge description¶

The incident offense category is slightly broader than the scale we need to identify marijuana arrests - fortunately, the Baltimore crime data includes another category, 'chargeDescription'. That is where we'll be able to see whether or not the charge is due to marijuana.

Unfortunately, this is not straightforward. From the first five rows of data, we can already see several issues:

1) There is an 'Unknown Charge'. The missing data issue is prevalent at every level of data collection.

For the sake of getting on with the analysis, I will make the generous assumption that all 'Unknown Charge' data has nothing to do with marijuana. This will mean that the data I find within the incident offenses I have chosen can be thought of as a lower bound. I would like to show that there is overall a high proportion of marijuana arrests, so if I can show that using a lower bound number, then that does nothing to take from the weight of the argument

2) The charge description includes both 'Possession-Marihuana' and 'Possess-Not Marihuana', so figuring out which charges include marijuana is not as simple as just grabbing all data which contains marijuana

Further, this uses an awfully odd spelling of marijuana. On that note, it is important to check whether marijuana is also spelled elsewhere in the data with a 'j' or if it is spelled incorrectly. We can use regex to search through!

I propose that likely mistakes, other than switching out the j for h could involve incorrect vowels and extra 'n's. It is also possible that some may report marijuana as cannabis instead

In [7]:
'''
matches() returns true if the regex matches the string
and false if it does not

It wraps the regex match call, since that does not
directly return a True/False value, but rather returns
a MatchObject instance if it matches or None if it does not

Further, it takes care of missing, or NaN values, whose type
is not string
'''
def matches(regex, string):
    if (type(string) != str):
        return False
    if (regex.match(string)):
        return True
    else:
        return False
In [8]:
# regex which should capture cannabis and possible shortenings of the word
cannabis_regex = re.compile('.*can.*', re.IGNORECASE)
# mask which filters out everything which does not match regex
cannabis_mask = arrest_table_drugs.apply(
    lambda row: matches(cannabis_regex, row['chargeDescription']),
    axis = 1)
# filtered data table from drug table
cannabis_arrests = arrest_table_drugs[cannabis_mask]

It is pretty striking that 94% of people arrested for marijuana are black and 91% are male. One could ask several questions from this:

1) What are the total demographics of the city of Baltimore?

2) Do blacks or males use marijuana in much greater quantities than the rest of the population?

To answer the first question we can look at some data provided in visual format from the baltimore department of planning at this link and from a website called towncharts, whose Baltimore data can be found here.

This data shows a huge discrepancy. Assuming the national trend holds true for Baltimore, which would certainly be a large assumption, police are arresting blacks and males at a much higher rate than non-blacks and non-males for the same crimes.

This is not particularly shocking, given the high tensions between Baltimore residents and police that seems to regularly make its way to the news, but it does seem to be a huge issue.

Now, of course there are likely many confounding factors. For example, one of the many potential situations could be if there are a higher proportion of black residents in socioeconomically less off communities. This could mean lower income coming into the city, which might mean that police might have less funding and may need to be more aggresive with arrests to try and get more money flowing in. There could be countless logical or illogical reasons made up for why this may be, and each one would require proper data analysis along with likely going in and surveying people to collect data which is not yet publically out there.

1.6 Examining likelihood for arrest, given use, by race¶

Let's take a look at the likelihood that one would be arrested for marijuana, given they are a user, based on race:

The probability that a black marijuana user is arrested can be broken down as follows

$P(B) = 0.63$ $P(User|B) = 0.16$ $P(B|Arrested For Marijuana) = 0.94$ $P(Arrested For Marijuana) = P(Arrested For Marijuana|Arrested) * P(Arrested)$ $= 0.1 * 100,000 / total population of baltimore = 10,000/ 620,000 = 0.016$ $P(Arrested For Marijuana|B) = P(B|Arrested For Marijuana) * P(Arrested For Marijuana) / P(B)$ $= 0.94 * 0.016 / 0.63 = 0.024$

2.4% of blacks in Baltimore are arrested for marijuana use

16% of blacks nationally use marijuana

That would mean that approximately 15% of black marijuana users in Baltimore are arrested

Let's take a look at the statistics for white users:

$P(B) = 0.30$ $P(User|B) = 0.14$ $P(B|Arrested For Marijuana) = 0.05$ $P(Arrested For Marijuana) = P(Arrested For Marijuana|Arrested) * P(Arrested)$ $= 0.05 * 100,000 / total population of baltimore = 5,000/ 620,000 = 0.016$ $P(Arrested For Marijuana|W) = P(W|Arrested For Marijuana) * P(Arrested For Marijuana) / P(W)$ $= 0.05 * 0.016 / 0.30 = 0.0027$

0.27% of whites in Baltimore are arrested for marijuana use

14% of whites nationally use marijuana

That would mean that approximately 2% of white marijuana users in Baltimore are arrested

That is a huge disparity - blacks are being arrested at a much higher rate than whites for the same crime in Baltimore

1.6 What percent of arrests are made for Marijuana?¶

Now that we examined some demographic anomalies, which I would highly recommend further exploration of through surveys and other forms of gathering data, let's come back to the original question at hand.

In [16]:
print('all arrests which involve marijuana, lower bound:',
    len(marijuana_arrests)/len(arrest_table))
print('all arrests which involve marijuana, middle bound:',
    len(marijuana_arrests)/(len(arrest_table) - unknown_offense_length))

    len(marijuana_arrests)/len(arrest_table_drugs))

all arrests which involve marijuana, lower bound: 0.09191795499770397
all arrests which involve marijuana, middle bound: 0.14584313665963358
drug arrests which involve marijuana: 0.3065730695596682

The lower bound for arrests involving marijuana, which assumes that none of the missing data included any marijuana arrests, 9%, is a sizeable proportion of total arrests. This is crazy considering that this is for a substance which is not pyschologically addictive, is less harmful than alcohol, and is even medically legal in the state of Maryland.

If the data without known incident offenses is missing completely at random, that would bring the total arrests due to marijuana to about 15%.

Further, 30% of drug arrests in Baltimore in 2015 involved marijuana. If the police department reallocated the time and money involved in finding, arresting, and prisoning marijuana users and used that instead for psychologically addictive drugs which cause much greater harm such as crack, cocaine and heroine, it would make a huge difference. They could be gaining a 50% in resources to track and catch dealers and users of these harder drugs, which would be a huge boost and could potentially be a catalyst for a safer Baltimore.

Now let's examine a little bit of DC data to see if there is an effect on marijuana legalization on other crime

2. Finding Data¶

State and Local Governments all over the United States are more and more often joining the trend of open sourcing their data for research purposes. Check out this site for information on which jurisdictions may have open data.

2.2 DC Marijuana Data¶

The beautiful thing about data analysis is that there is so much data out there on such a large variety of topics that it can generally be assumed that if one source does not have everything needed to carry out an analysis, the requisit data will exist elsewhere. And if does not exist in a readily accessible form, it can be scraped from a website or even created based on other existing data if necessary.

DC would be ideal because marijuana was legalized recreationally effective February 2015 and it would have been interesting to observe the trends before and after legalization. Unfortunately, I found that the DC crime Data does not include drug crimes.

Not to despair, we can still look at the change in crimes in DC before and after the legalization of marijuana.

def isViolent(crime):
    return crime == 'HOMICIDE' \
        or crime == 'ASSAULT W/DANGEROUS WEAPON' \
        or crime == 'SEX ABUSE'

violent_crime_2012_mask = dc_crime_2012.apply(lambda row: isViolent(row['OFFENSE']), axis=1)
violent_crime_2013_mask = dc_crime_2013.apply(lambda row: isViolent(row['OFFENSE']), axis=1)
violent_crime_2014_mask = dc_crime_2014.apply(lambda row: isViolent(row['OFFENSE']), axis=1)
violent_crime_2015_mask = dc_crime_2015.apply(lambda row: isViolent(row['OFFENSE']), axis=1)
violent_crime_2016_mask = dc_crime_2016.apply(lambda row: isViolent(row['OFFENSE']), axis=1)
violent_crime_2012 = dc_crime_2012[violent_crime_2012_mask]
violent_crime_2013 = dc_crime_2013[violent_crime_2013_mask]
violent_crime_2014 = dc_crime_2014[violent_crime_2014_mask]

Interestingly enough, there is a barely perceptible difference in either overall crime reported or violent crime between 2014, when marijuana was illegal, and 2015, after legalization.

That being said, it can be seen from the data that both crime overall and violent crime had been rising from 2012 to 2014, and then had dropped between 2014 and 2015 and again between 2015 and 2016.

This is promising that there may be a positive effect on overall crime, but of course this should be verified with much more research on the topic. There are countless confounding variables which would make it very difficult to verifiably discern that the correlation may be explained in part by the legalization of marijuana
